text=:Category: Varia%0a:Expansion: Cold and Warm Colors%0a:Author: VikramM%0a:Original: [[Articles.TheColorNamingDebate|TheColorNamingDebate]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.kevinx|kevinx]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 05.05.2021 - 21:23%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210506-184808-37520#%0a* [-06.05.2021 - 11:48-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210506-184808-37520#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aAn MIT study probed how warm and cold colors differ in their division of the spectrum and in the number of words used to describe color that fall into each category. In this study the warm colors are considered to be red, orange, and yellow while the cold colors are green, blue.%0a%0aThe study looked at over 100 languages and the general finding was that the warm side of the color spectrum had more words or finer divisions of the colors than the cold side. One possible reason mentioned in the study is that objects or entities in the foreground of a image or setting are often composed dominantly of warmer colors while the backgrounds can be mostly composed of colder colors. %0a%0aThe study does not encompass all languages from all environments, so the researchers may move on the study how color is used in languages in locations with extreme climates such as deserts to see if the relationships between the foreground and background of scenes and color naming are the same. %0a%0aSource: https://news.mit.edu/2017/analyzing-language-color-0918#%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
